ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 8
 illustrates the photoluminescence properties of WO3/N-CQDs at different concentrations. The optical properties of WO3/N-CQDs were observed using Photoluminescence spectroscopy with excitation wavelength at 350 nm. The emission peak is observable at 590–610 nm with the center peak at 605 nm. It can be seen clearly that the PL intensity of WO3/N-CQDs is remarkably quenched with addition of NCQDs. Firstly, at the lower amount of N-CQDs, the PL intensity is quenched at the highest rate. The increasing amount of N-CQDs lowers the quenching effect of the PL intensity. This might be due to the overdose effect that is mentioned earlier. The overdose effect tends to form aggregate to arrange larger particles structure (Zhang et al., 2016). The PL’s lower intensity indicates reduced charge carrier recombination, which is caused by photons emission from the electron-hole pair recombination (Jamila et al., 2020). The addition of nitrogen in CQDs corresponds to the enhanced quantum excessiveness of synthesized photocatalysts and then effectively allocated the generated electrons from the surface of WO3 (Ching Sim et al., 2018). Consequently, the reduction of charge carrier recombination resulting in increased photocatalytic activity (Fig. 9
).
